events.name: IWD: UX & design sprint workshops
events.description:
We're looking to hear your success stories! Please fill in our call for proposals by March 24th here:
https://goo.gl/forms/Sxl8JU11hJbSylCr1

Celebrating International Women's Day

Women Techmakers The Netherlands will kick off our first event in collaboration with Makerversity and Ladies That UX Amsterdam and the fantastic support of Google's diversity program!

Join us for the first evening of a two-part celebration! This first part is focused on user experience, with a UX presentation and Q&A session by our friends at Ladies That UX Amsterdam, followed by a Design Sprint Day 0 workshop.

The Design Sprint from Google Ventures is a five-day process for answering critical business questions through design, prototyping, and testing ideas with customers. It's a “greatest hits” of business strategy, innovation, behavior science, design thinking, and more—packaged into a battle-tested process that any team can use.

The second part will be on April 25th; see the event page for details.

Agenda

(Please note that this may be subject to change.)

18:15   Walk-in
18:30  Introduction to Women Techmakers
18:40 Crimes against design: how to lead clients into the right direction by Darina Krutiy; As designers we do our work most of the time for a client, project manager or a boss. There are people with whom it is challenging to communicate about design. And there are people who leave you wondering how come crimes against design are not legally punishable. Daryna will share some of her experiences with clients and bosses and discuss ways how to interact with various types of the 'tough' ones. 
19:30  UX panel Q/A session
19:40  Break
19:50  Design Sprint Day 0; An introduction to Google’s revolutionary problem solving technique followed by a brainstorming session where we’ll altogether have to come across with a problem—and a solution!
21:10   Closing and drinks
21:30  Doors closed

Who's welcome?

Our group connects women who are working in technology, are learning about technology, or are just interested in technology in the Netherlands. Our events are open to tech enthusiasts of all genders and ages.

Location & host

Makerversity Amsterdam is in the heart of Amsterdam, near the NEMO museum. We recommend traveling by public transportation; exit from Amsterdam Central Station turning left towards the NEMO museum. Continue walking along the water of Oosterdok, past the library and conservatory, crossing the bridge to Hanneke's Boom. Continue straight for a bit and take the first bridge on your right. Keep right along the water. It should be roughly a 20 minute walk.

Partners

This event is in collaboration with Ladies that UX Amsterdam and SheSharp.

Support for this event is made possible by Google's Women Techmakers diversity program.

events.name: Hash Code 2018
events.description:
Think you could come up with a way to optimize Internet coverage for Project Loon balloons? Or how about routing Google Street View cars through Paris?

Step into the shoes of a Google engineer and tackle these types of challenges during Hash Code, a team-based programming competition for students and professionals (18+) across Europe, the Middle East and Africa organized by Google. You pick your team and programming language, we pick a real-life engineering problem to solve. Are you up for the challenge?
The competition is divided into two stages:
* an Online Qualification Round on 1st March at 18:30 CET
For this round, your team can participate from wherever you’d like, including one of our Hash Code hubs. Hubs allow for teams in the same location (eg. city or university) to compete side-by-side in a more fun and exciting environment.
* a Final Round on 1st April
Top scoring teams from the Online Qualification Round will be invited to Google Paris to compete in the Final Round of the competition.

Find some teammates, sign up today at g.co/hashcode and we'll see you at the UvA!

Your organizers

events.name: IWD Netherlands 2018 : Building a new Horizon
events.description:
We are proud to be hosting the 2018 International Women's Day Celebration, a women's tech conference, open to everyone. This event will highlight the stories of our growing female community of designers, developers, and technology entrepreneurs.

Agenda
(Please note that this may be subject to change.)

17:00 Walk-in & Dinner*
17:30 Speechless: Becoming a confident public speaker -
Lee Boonstra (https://www.linkedin.com/in/leeboonstra/)
19:30 Becoming an employable, self-educated programmer - Louise Bicker Caarten**
19:45 Open panel
20:10 Closing and drinks*
20:45 Doors closed

*Food and beverage are sponsored by Q42

**Abstract: A few years ago I graduated from university with a BSc in Psychology and absolutely no idea of what to do with my life. I ended up passively accepting jobs that felt demeaning and uninspiring. Frustrations mounted, until one day I realized that I needed to set a goal, and stick to it: I decided to become a programmer. I took a radical approach and quit my job to focus on learning to program full-time. Join me in this talk to hear about my process of setting a goal, the steps I took to achieve it, and how I ended up in New York to attend the Recurse Center in pursuit of a career as a programmer.

• Important to know
Our events are open to tech enthusiasts of all genders and ages.
Code of conduct: https://gdgnetherlands.org/conduct

• About Q42
Q42 is a strategic technology agency; or as we like to say, we're 80 nerds who like to make things with impact, things that make people smile.

We've made Q42 into a place where, next to our work for clients, everyone gets room to run with their own ideas and dreams. From products and labels to independent startups — and everything inbetween. We call these ventures.
LessonUp, Turtleblaze, Micr.io and Hack the Planet are examples of these endeavours.

'A strategic technology agency', say some. 'Nerds', say others. If we're honest? We just really love to write good code.

Create a GCP account
For this tutorial you will need a GCP account. If you don't have one yet, you can create a free trial account. A valid billing account is required, in order to make use of Google Cloud resources. events.name: Firebase & PWAs, what a great match!
events.description:
You might know Firebase. You might know a thing or two about PWA's. But have you seen them combined? Join us for our first Web meetup!

Build a PWA with Angular and Firebase with a score of 100 on Lighthouse.
Adding PWA capabilities to your app is easy with adding @angular/pwa via ng cli. However, you need to do more on your app to create best experiences for your users on multiple platforms. This session will cover what you need to do to optimise your PWA for the production with the guidelines of best practices and platform optimisations.

These optimisations include iOS compatibility, web app manifest and ngsw configuration along with firebase server configuration. Önder will demonstrate the steps required for delivering a PWA on Firebase which will be available immediately for the audience.

The Ins and Outs of Firebase
Want to speed up your development? Then have a look with us at Firebase. Firebase offers numerous resources that work out of the box, so you don’t have to develop them. With the use of live apps, Ruben will demonstrate how to use the database to communicate in real-time, what is required to host an app online, and how to create easily reusable functions.

18:00 – Doors open. Food & drinks provided
18:45 – Önder Ceylan - Build a PWA with Angular and Firebase with a score of 100 on Lighthouse
19:45 – Break
20:00 – Ruben van der Leun - The Ins and Outs of Firebase
20:45 – Pool, laughing, networking and drinks until someone kicks us out!

events.description:

Jairzinno Henriquez - Building the GDG NL app.
In this talk we'll the cover how the GDG NL app (currently in beta) was build.
You'll get to see which decisions were made and how to build an app from scratch while sharing your code for other platforms such as the web and Firebase Cloud functions.

Stefan Mitev - Animations and motion in Flutter
Animations can make your application easy to understand, more engaging and fun to use. However, animations are hard, aren't they? Fortunately, not in Flutter! In this talk, we'll take a look at what the framework has to offer for building quick and yet impressive animations.

The contents of these talk target beginners of Flutter and no prior knowledge about animations is required. However, a nice to have will be having a basic understanding of how Flutter widgets work.

Bio:
Sara Gerion is software engineer in DAZN, a platform revolutionising the sport industry. Her role is to help developing and maintaining its core functional logic and operations. Previously working as a backend developer at Superhero Cheesecake, an award winning digital production agency. She is also co-founder & director of tech at SheSharp (S#E), a non-profit association in Amsterdam which fosters diversity in tech and entrepreneurship & provides an open and safe community for under-represented demographics.

Roxanne Groenenberg is one of the co-organizers of Ladies that UX Amsterdam, a global community that aims to empower women to claim their voice and role in product creation processes. In her daily work she is a User Experience Designer at idean, where she consults different clients in order to improve their overall user experience, from business processes to actual products.

Suzanne Leow is marketing manager for Google, at the Google Cloud team working on initiatives to drive awareness for Google's solutions & demonstrating customers how to transform their business with cloud technology. Her experience encompasses marketing strategy, integrated experiences and campaigns. Before joining Google, Suzanne worked for a technology education startup where she was responsible for international strategy development. Suzanne is passionate to share her joy about both innovation and style.

Lotte Leufkens is an engineer, social impact entrepreneur and former topsport player. Ms. Leufkens commits herself to innovate within handicapped and elderly healthcare, and speaks about entrepreneurship, leadership & innovation. In 2016, she founded her start-up “CloudCuddle”, which makes tentbeds for families with handicapped children. Her commitment and drive have resulted in many awards & achievements, such as becoming Student Entrepreneur of the Netherlands in 2017 & winning the TEDxAmsterdam Women Startup Award.

Lee Boonstra is sales engineer at Google. As a sales engineer, Lee assist the sales team with technical knowledge. She visits (potential) customers to demonstrate the technology and to give technical consultancy/ trainings. Lee speaks regularly at seminars and conferences and writes blogposts and articles for various magazines and websites. She also wrote a book for O'Reilly: Hands-on Sencha Touch 2.

Vanessa Ho is a Backend Developer at Info.nl and Founder of Let’s Coding Together. Previously a environmental project manager, she made the career switch to software development 1.5 years ago. She's helping to build up a encouraging community of women coders through mentorship, workshops and providing spaces for people to meet and code. Her passions outside of the tech world include rock climbing and trying new cereals.

Themis Athanassiadou has more than 6 years of experience in working as the interface between technology and end users. Currently she works as a support engineer for Developer Tools at Atlassian. Themis started out as a scientist. She has a PhD in computational astrophysics from the University of Illinois, and then worked as a postdoctoral research associate at Arizona State University. Other than science and technology, Themis is passionate about dancing & languages; she teaches dance & speaks more than 5languages

events.name: Building Voice Apps
events.description:
Join us for our first cross-GDG meetup!
Øyvind Randa, a data scientist/developer and fellow GDG organizer in Bergen, Norway will join us for a talk on building cross platform voice apps. Next to him we will have our very own Google Assistant GDE Eliza Camber talk about the Google Assistant.

Eliza Camber - Personalize for each user and device
What sets apart a good action is personalizing the experience for each user, adapting to their needs and offer the best experience for whichever device the user is currently using. Customizing the responses, storing information and manipulating the medium of the displayed response, can all be achieved by learning how to leverage the AoG SDK. Together we will learn the differences between the DialogFlow SDK and the AoG SDK, how to perform all the above and some best practices that will help you build your action faster and better. The language we're going to use during this talk is Kotlin

Øyvind Randa - Building cross platform voice apps
Have you ever tried to build cross-platform voice apps for Alexa and Google Assistant? How can we keep the user experience consistent over both platforms with the same codebase?
We will see how Jovo Framework can help us solve these challenges. Jovo framework is a cross-platform framework for building voice apps for Alexa and Google Assistant. I will be live code a small demo on how it works.

Schedule:

18:00 Dinner
18:45 Opening
19:00 Personalize for each user and device app by Eliza Camber
19:45 Break
20:00 Building cross platform voice apps by Øyvind Randa
20:45 Drinks

events.name: Flutter Learnings & State management with Firebase
events.description:
Join us for a meetup at Triple in Alkmaar for sessions about the learnings the folks at Triple made and how to do state management in Flutter with Firebase.

Learnings from developing the Veilig ID app
We will share our journey and learnings developing the Veilig ID app in Flutter. We challenged ourselves to deliver a fast and fluid app in a short timeframe

Flutter state management with Firebase - Jairzinno Henriquez
Flutter allows you to build beautiful apps with great UI. But any serious app will have to manage state and it's business logic and connect with a backend.
Firebase is a great platform for supporting your apps. During this talk we'll look at how you can connect your Flutter app to Firebase and how you can manage your state and business logic.
